**The Ruin** (ch.16 of `unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e`) has the most thoroughly past ruin. Three converging signals from the text:

1. **Explicit temporal gulf**: "in the ground's hard grip, till a hundred generations of people have passed" — the builders are archaeologically remote, not recently lost.
2. **Anonymous, stakeless spectatorship**: The speaker has no name, no personal grief, no genealogical tie to the fallen city. Every sentence is third-person past-tense description — no "I", no dream-visions of the old world returning, no search for a replacement patron.
3. **The poem enacts its subject**: The manuscript is physically decayed, leaving multiple `[...]` lacunae. Even the text is a ruin.

The Wanderer (ch.11) is disqualified because his speaker is still alive in exile, still seeking a new lord, still dreaming of clasping his dead kinsman's knees — the loss is present-tense suffering, not archaeological remoteness. Saqaliya (ch.21) is most disqualified: Iqbal explicitly names himself heir ("To sorrow-fated Iqbal, your mourning was bequeathed"), calls himself "the dust of that caravan," and plans to carry Sicily's grief to Hindustan as a living transmission. That ruin is the most alive of the three.
